content.description: Another fun moderate
content.location: East end of the cliffs left of the corner.

content.description: CRAZY, unique route. Rope up at the base and head through some less than vertical moves to an offwidthish move getting under the roof. Walk the plank to your left, clipping at your knees as you go. After finishing the plank, fire up through the crux on THIN and reachy moves with crap for feet.
content.protection: 7 bolts to anchors. Two fixed draws.

content.description: Hard start on crimpers!  You may want to stick clip the first bolt.   Fun climb.  I didn't really find an obvious crux; the route is fairly sustained.
content.location: Route # 26 in Burton and Steagall (1997).  Just to the right of the often climbed "Claim to Fame", the 11a that is more like a 10b with one hard move going for the anchors.

content.description: Some loose rock and a seemingly runout third bolt make for a less than awesome time.
content.location: Just to the right of Jack's Back, the rightmost route on this wall.

content.description: Challenging start!
Great climbing through pumpy, overhung rock. Watch the right handed gaston sidepull after the second bolt (crux)! Great lead, and as with all Jacks climbs, well protected.

Good route that is actually solid at the grade (Jack's Canyon??!!) with two separate crux's, one low and one high with great movement in between.  Very fun and could be pretty moderate redpoint but would be harder onsight as some holds are hidden!!
content.protection: Well protected sport route with 5 bolts to fixed anchor up top.
content.location: In the center section of the Cracker Jack Cliffs just right of Jack & Jill go Bolting (10a) and left of Charlie Don't Send (9-ugly climb).

content.description: The left-most route on the Firedance/Enemy Wind wall.

Fun climbing, a nice moderate. This is the first route right of the obvious corner and route # 57 in the guidebook. Kinda high first bolt but its very easy to get to. Just get past the second bolt the route eases,Â
content.location: East end of the cliffs in the corner.

content.description: Fun route.
content.location: Two routes left of the roof.

content.description: Pull on some hard edges and pockets past the first bolt, then continue up easier arete to a rest under a roof. Pull the technical moves over the roof and continue up a groove to the anchors.
Good first lead. Classic!
content.location: On the separate boulder at the east end of Cracker Jack Cliffs, starts in the creek bed.

content.description: Start next to or on top of a small talus pile.  Follow up an arete that has easy climbing down low to more difficult moves up top.  The climb begins to trend left after the second bolt.  You'll encounter slopers, jugs, underclings, a few crimps, and a crack move or two to get up SJ. Very fun climb to jump on, especially if the Sinker corner is busy.
content.protection: 4 bolts, to 2 bolt anchor on top.
content.location: Located about 100 ft to the climbers right of the Sinker corner.  The wall has 3 bolts lines on it and Saucy Jack is the rightmost of these climbs.  The start is a few feet left of a couple of bushes and a tree.

content.description: Pockety climbing up a bulge.
content.protection: Crash pad.  If the canyon is flooded, you can hop on your crash pad and paddle it to the climb.

content.description: Thin, hard start down low using holds well to the right of the first bolt gets you to some bigger holds and then into a mini-corner for some more interesting moves to a big ledge of poor rock quality for the anchors.
content.location: The route is the first route to the left of the popular corner route, Best Seller. A low first bolt protects the route's crux off the ground.

content.description: Start to the left of the first bolt. Cruxy thin climbing leads past the first bolt. From there, the holds get a bit better but the pump mounts as you edge up the slightly off-vertical face past many fair holds. Hang in there! A classic for the area.

Left most route starting just right of a debris pile. Climb is slightly crowded by a tree that threatens to impale a falling climber if they should fall from the final hard move. A shoe can be carried up and used as an unusual bit of protection, as it is easy enough to slip the shoe on the offending spike at the good rest just before the last moves.
content.protection: 5 bolts + 2 shut anchor + optional hiking shoe ;)
content.location: About 100 feet left of walking the plank

content.description:
Just left of the crack (Betty Cracker 5.9) this route starts easily enough but soon after the moves and holds get thin.   

  Vertical route with crimpy holds on that super grippy dark grey rock.  It's nice.
content.location: While walking in from the main trail you'll come across a large low angle boulder (sinker 5.5)just above the wash bottom.  Directly in front of the boulder is a courtyard that gets early morning shade year round.  Third route from the right on the south facing wall.

content.description: Great route following a crack through some loose apearing rock. Great warm up and also one of the better 5.10s at Jacks canyon!
Starting on a semi-sloped belay area the route travels up and right.  The final moves skirt a large roof at the top before reaching the anchor.
content.location: Main wall at Cracker Jack Cliffs in front of Large shade tree.  Going left to right - this is the second route on the right.

content.description: Pretty mellow 5.10. Good route.
content.location: East end of cracker jack cliffs to the left of a roof.

content.description: Fun overhung route climbing great pockets and edges.
Nice and Mellow, a good moderate
Low angle slab through two small buldges to finish off with large holds.
content.location: Continue walking past the Firedance area on the path for another 120ft.

content.description: Fun route with pockets and side pulls to the top.
An OK crimpy route.
content.location: Between Jacks back and Jacks in a Hole.

content.description: Pretty fun route that is well protected and moderate movement over stone.  Good fun pockets and jugs lead to the fixed anchors.  Fun moves but would be a better route if it were only longer.
content.protection: 4 Bolts to a fixed anchor on top of ledge.  I would recommend some long runners for anchors if top-roping.
content.location: Route is almost dead center in middle of Cracker Jack Cliffs and usually has morning shade and afternoon Heat!!!

content.description: Easy chimney that can be top roped using the anchors for Jack Off
content.protection: Top rope this climb from Jack Off anchors
content.location: Jack Off Chimney is the chimney climb directly behind Jack Off

content.description: GREAT route for the grade!!  Follow 4 bolts up arete/edge of cliff to fixed anchors.  Steep climbing down low for the grade but jugs will save the day!  Very good route, don't miss!
content.protection: Four bolts and fixed anchors provide a good rap.
content.location: Left hand side of wall on well featured stone in about dead center of Cracker Jack Cliffs area about 100 feet from a prominent large tree you can't miss.

content.description:
Bouldery start - guide book indicates using a clip stick for the first bolt (although unnecessary). Clipping and moving past the first bolt is likely the crux.  This route provides fun sustained climbing.   

  Look for very positive large flake (well chalked) just above the 2nd bolt.  If you get any part of this you're golden!! 

  Climb steep route over several bulges using small pockets.  Sounds like fun eh?
content.location: Middle of the main wall at Cracker Jack Cliffs.  Right of large shade tree by a few routes.

content.description: This route is great. A true 5.11a in my opinion (if you have been to jacks, you would know what I mean here.) Nice pocketed climbing over three different roofs to the chain anchor!
Be warned: the handholds are sharp on this one.
content.protection: Four bolts to a two bolt anchor
content.location: Route to the left of 'Jack Pot'

content.description: Hard, reachy start which is ok once you figure it out. Beta given in comments :)
content.location: In the little alcove beside Jack Jumped.

content.description: Just left of jack be quick. Starts on face then through roof to anchors. Over the roof there are 2 ways, either big powerful moves left or small powerful moves right. Then a good crimpy section to finish. Certainly worth doing
Book rates this at 5.11a, though I think it goes a little easier than that so I down graded it here. Stellar route though, with great holds goint up through the overhung arete.
Awesome route that is continuous good movement with a funky hold/thumb undercling crux up high.  One of my favorite routes at Cracker Jack Cliffs, Must Do!!
content.protection: Five Bolts will get you to the fixed anchors up top for your rappel.
content.location: This route is about 5 feet right of the route, Jack Off (8) and just left of Total Lack of Jack (10c) in the center of the Cracker Jack Cliffs.  Route 32.1 in the guidebook.  Rapple off and have a great day.

content.description: Start on the good hold and crank through a V6 consisting of four moves on small pockets, left, right, bump right, deadpoint left.  Use feet that set you up for the deadpoint left instead of the big foot holds. Clip the second bolt then have somebody send up some huevos rancheros so you can eat while you climb 5.10 to the anchors.
content.location: In the tree on the right side of the bulge (right of Firedance and Enemy Wind)

content.description: Bottom section cruxy with lunge from bad left sidepull. Then awkwardness getting your feet up on the ledge. Get ready for the official crux which requires you reach high to stab a small pocket and try to clip a 3rd bolt with lack of any good feet (I skipped this bolt!)  Then crank on to better holds and a 5.11 finish. Phew.
content.location: To the right of Walking the Plank.

content.description: This is the farthest left of the three routes that start by climbing thru very featured, pocketed rock until about 20'. Though this one may not be as consistent as it's more classic neighbors to the right, it is still well worth doing.
Bouldery roof start to easy climbing above. Think...Body tension going over the roof (crux)!
The crux is about halfway up.  I required a blind cross through, but other people just reach through.  Either way, it's a high quality route.
content.location: to the farthest left hand side of the Cracker Jack wall.  Route in the middle of the wall.  The wall can't be missed because of the super featured pockets (natural) to the 2nd bolt.

climbs.name: Every Things It's Cracked Up To Be

content.description: Another line with some bolted crack. Crux at the top if you stay on route.
content.protection: Four bolts plus two more at the top
content.location: between Crack 'em Up (on the left) and Saucy Jack (on the right).

content.description:
The formation at this area forms a shallow book type feature.  On your right you will find Big Plans 10a and on your left is Enemy Wind.   

  The route looks innocent enough but is a bit longer and is sustained in steepness.  The guidebook warns you to "hold your breath and run for the anchors".  Translation...you'll might be gassed but keep going!
content.location: Keep walking past Crosstown Traffic on the far end of Cracker Jack Cliffs.  While at the base you'll walk over a tree with a low trunk system.  While walking over the tree, look straight ahead to Enemy Wind.

content.description: Climb up to a right facing seam which leads to an  improbable looking roof. A fun, bouldery sequence gets you over the roof to a tricky finish. I was pleasently surprised with this climb!
content.location: 2nd route from the left most end of Cracker Jack Cliff.

content.description: A great route with fun movement that diagnals left up the wall.
content.location: On the west end of cracker jack cliffs.

content.description: Crux at the roof,short and crimpy pockets over the roof than done. Not a stellar route but worth doing if your in the area.
content.location: On the east end of Cracker Jack cliffs under the left side roof.

content.description: Crux half way up. Not very hard if you know how to finger jam.
content.protection: Bolted. I think I remember three bolts plut the two at the top.
content.location: Just right of the sinker (the big boulder in the creek with a short bolted line.

content.description: This is a really nice route that goes up on nice big moves to an overhang finish. The guidebook originally rated it 10d and then upgraded it to 11a. If you move right at the top, rather than going straight up the bulge, you may think this is the easiest 11a on the planet.
content.location: This route starts just right of the corner system where Best Seller is found. Far left end of the Cracker Jack Cliffs, just right of a big overhang.

content.description: Follow route crossing a grungy roof up top.  Originally this route was dirty and loose but has cleaned up in the last 10 years.  Large platform area to clip chain anchors.
content.protection:
5 bolts to chain anchors 

  Use draws for your Top Roping to avoid wear!
content.location: Sunny south facing wall with 4 routes on it.  While facing the crags this wall is the next formation left of the shady tree (common pack dropping area). Route is the furthest right on this wall.

content.description: Either yard on awkward pockets or jump to pass the starting bulge, then continue up the thin face on sharp holds to more forgiving moves at the very top. Reachy in spots, with some tricky moves.
content.location: The second bolt line to the left of Jack Be Nimble, the obvious roof climb a few dozen yards past the Sinker area.

content.description: Great sidepull, delicate ballancy moves going through the crux with bomber hidden jugs over the roof to pull yourself to glory!
Just right of shallow book climb route using steaming & face climbing techniques.
content.location: Keep walking past Crosstown Traffic on the far end of Cracker Jack Cliffs. While at the base you'll walk over a tree with a low trunk system. Looking to your right you'll see a shallow book system with a route on the right.  This is Big Plans

content.description: Yet another good moderate
content.location: Two routes left of the corner

content.description: Very nice route that mixes some crack moves with face cranking on big holds. One of the better routes in the Canyon.
content.location: On the leftmost section of the Cracker Jack Cliffs area. The route is in a corner just right of a big overhang.

content.description: Short boulder problem involving shallow pockets and very limited feet to pull the bulge, then a much easier jaunt to clip the anchors.
content.location: Between Big Plans and Huecos Rancheros, on the fairly blank looking bulge.

content.description: Crimpy start to easier climbing above 2nd bolt
content.location: Between Virtuous Reality and Back to Basics.

content.description: Good moderate route but definitely solid 5.9 (kinda rare for Jacks Canyon I know!).  One crux move to safely clip the second bolt and another awaits higher up.  Very cool movement and I do recommend this route, just don't do it first thing in the morning like we did!!
content.protection: 4 Bolts will get you to the fixed anchors on ledge above for your rappel.
content.location: Located somewhat left of the center of the Cracker Jack Cliffs; look for a indistinct corner (with another great 5.9), this route is about 15 feet right of the corner and just above some small blocks on the ground.  Route # 27 in the guidebook.

content.description: A decent route that climbs the left side of the wall.
content.location: The left-most route on the wall, two left of jack frost.

content.description: Climbs the blunt arete.
content.protection: 4 bolts to anchors on ledge right of "Ida-who".
content.location: Just left of Jack Frost

content.description: Most of the routes are south facing. To the far left (east) end, one can find morning shade. A number of routes at all levels.
